Linear Search:
Linear search is a very simple search algorithm. In this type of search, a sequential search is done for all items one by one.
Every item is checked and if a match is found then that particular item is returned, otherwise the search continues till the end of the data collection.

//Not efficient for large arrays, since it has to search for item manually through all the elements

-----
Example 1:

//Main.java

class Main{
    public static void main (String[] args) {
        int[] a = {38, 52, 9, 18, 6, 62, 13};
        
        int item = 13; //search element
        int temp = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<a.length; i++)
        {
            if(a[i]==item)
            {
                System.out.println("Element is fount at index position: "+i);
                temp = 1;
            }
        }
        if(temp == 0)
        {
            System.out.println("Element not found");
        }
    }
}

o/p:
Element is fount at index position: 6

-----
Example 2:

//Main.java

class Main{
    public static void main (String[] args) {
        int[] a = {38, 52, 9, 18, 6, 62, 13};
        
        int item = 88; //search element
        int temp = 0;
        for(int i=0;i<a.length; i++)
        {
            if(a[i]==item)
            {
                System.out.println("Element is fount at index position: "+i);
                temp = 1;
            }
        }
        if(temp == 0)
        {
            System.out.println("Element not found");
        }
    }
}

o/p:
Element not found

